## 1. Alias Regex Cheatsheet

All aliases in TorilLib use `#` as the prefix.  
Mudlet alias regex uses **capture groups** `()` — each group becomes `matches[2]`, `matches[3]`, etc.  
`matches[1]` is always the full matched string; your captures start at `[2]`.

| Pattern | What it captures | Example input |
|---------|-----------------|---------------|
| `(\S+)` | One word, no spaces | `#cmd word` |
| `(\S*)` | One word, optional (can be empty) | `#cmd` or `#cmd word` |
| `\s*(.*)$` | Everything after a space, optional | `#cmd rest of line` |
| `(\S+)\s*(.*)$` | First word + rest of line | `#cmd arg1 rest` |
| `(\S*)\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)` | Up to 4 separate words | `#cmd a b c d` |

### Standard 5-arg alias regex (what #cvar uses)

```
^#cvar\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)\s*(\S*)$
```

Captures: `matches[2]` through `matches[6]`  
= `action`, `name`, `val1`, `val2`, `val3`, `val4`

> **Tip:** Use `\s*(\S*)` (not `\s+(\S+)`) so all args are optional.
> An unmatched optional group gives you an **empty string** `""`, not nil,
> because `string.trim` is applied. Always compare with `~= ""`.

