## 2. The Variable Block Pattern

Every alias starts with a clean variable block at the top. This makes it
easy to see what data the alias works with at a glance and change arg
positions without hunting through logic.

```lua
-- ── ARG BLOCK ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
--  matches[2] = arg1 ... matches[N] = argN
--  string.trim() collapses whitespace; unmatched groups return ""

local action = string.trim(matches[2] or "")   -- add / del / list / etc.
local name   = string.trim(matches[3] or "")   -- variable name
local val1   = string.trim(matches[4] or "")   -- value slot 1
local val2   = string.trim(matches[5] or "")   -- value slot 2
local val3   = string.trim(matches[6] or "")   -- value slot 3
local val4   = string.trim(matches[7] or "")   -- value slot 4

-- ── STATE BLOCK ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
--  Pull persistent data from charData once at the top.
--  Always pass `true` as second arg to get a table (not nil) if missing.

local store = charData:get("cvar", true)       -- returns {} if not yet set
```

Rules:
- Always `or ""` on matches so you never get a nil error
- Always `string.trim()` every arg
- Pull `charData` once at the top, mutate `store`, save at the bottom
- Never read `charData` twice in the same alias — use `store` throughout

